Article: Sharing Economy From A Policy Management Perspective
Genres: ['Society - Culture', 'Economics', 'Invention - Technology']
Tags: ['Precariat', 'Future', 'The Dark side', 'Sharing Economy', 'E-Commerce']
Creators: ['Tráº§n Tiáº¿n']
Date: 2020-11-26


Description:

The competitive advantages of the sharing economy compared with the traditional business model.

The sharing economy is posing many risks in the rights of both service providers and the clients.

The impacts of the sharing economy to social aspects in the future.

Content:

A sharing economy is defined as a peer-to-peer (P2P) business model, which can be broadly interpreted as the partnership between â€˜peersâ€™ on certain online platforms. Such a business model thrives on the very notion that there are always someone providing/supplying the very services/goods that some others are thirsting for, for the time being.

To demonstrate, should you have a spare room, you can post it on Airbnb and lease it to those traveling or going on a business; should you have space on your hailed means, you can use Lyft / Uber / Grab to lease that seat to someone; if you have extra money, you can lend it to others through a peer-to-peer credit network; or should you ever thirst for work, you can always seek new employees on Upwork.

1. Sharing from economy

According to data from the Brookings Institution [1], personal transports are all too idle for 95% of their lives, so are spare bedrooms in any house. This major factor scales down good prices within a shared economy, which then plummets to a much lower level compared to ordinary marketâ€™s. To put into perspective, Statista did indeed evidence that Airbnbâ€™s room rates went violently lower than any normal hotel roomâ€™s (in all major cities) [2].

Which is understandable, for the sharing economy does actually deploy community resources, wherein each individual takes care of his/her own not-too-large-in-volume business. In case of Airbnb, either the room construction, the pick-up and drop-off, room cleaning task, or high-quality photos to post on the platform rest entirely on the lessora. On the other hand, tenants (and the Airbnb community), in turn, take on a supervisory role, through star ratings, commenting or reporting to Airbnb to cull the â€œscabby sheepsâ€. Airbnb. after all, mainly deals with technical issues, technology, risk control and marketing - which are, in all appearances, for their own sake [3].

It also applies to Grab, on which the drivers shoulder the responsibility for refueling, maintaining the transport, and improving their right attitudes toward customers. Given that the founders still are conducting job training activities. drivers, after all, are the ones in charge of their work.

On the other hand, the world's leading hotel and transportation corporations must take on everything (at much more perplexing levels) merely to provide the same services. They drain enormous amounts of capital to invest in construction, transportation (given that the topography, land use and construction of such a Brobdingnagian project itself is an arduous problem); enormous manpower so that the employees some departments would hardly go redundant whilst others running short; they do shoulder all risks and appear as legal entities to get directly exposed to laws [4].

This way, the costs of a 5-star hotel room must cover that of maintaining empty rooms and â€œfeedâ€ other hotel employees, from the counter staff, the janitor to C-level shareholders. Such an entangled model gets hotel owners to step up the convoluted cost and promotion processes more cautiously, whilst on the opposite side, Grab / Uber / Airbnb are splurging most of their capital budget on promotion programs (for otherwise, the financial flow would be idle) [5].

Such a fierce conflict has paved the very way for many international lawsuits (including Vietnamâ€™s), in which traditional corporations desperately blaspheme technology companies prospering on sharing economies. While traditional corporations have forevermore been legally bound to (and taxed by) certain frameworks, their startup counterparts are not grouped and less severely taxed for they do hardly own any real estate or production facilities [6].

Exacerbating the situation, whilst traditional corporations are as much responsible for many a legal document related to contracts, insurance and additional responsibility per new employees, either Grab, Uber, Airbnb or any other similar sharing platforms only deal with "partners" and take on limited liability [6].

Given the very nature of the same services/products, the factors behind the two sides must have been chalk and cheese.

2. To every cost and risk

As a rule, recent technology-companies-involved lawsuits have evidenced the publicâ€™s ardent supports for tech corps. Which is somewhat understandable, for Airbnb offers elegant rooms, friendly hosts, private space at much lower costs than hotelsâ€™; Grab / Uber / Lyft is at service for their low-cost transportation and friendly drivers, let alone the series of seemingly-never-ending discounts.

A sharing economy model has every upper hand over traditional models (as aforeargued), forasmuch as consumers has every reason not to mind how they actually operate. Bizarrely enough, people are seeing sharing economies as bettering service qualities.

Nevertheless, they should be wary, sooner or later.

Together with the rigorous old-school process, laws, from macro-scale (stateâ€™s) to micro-scale (association) are to keep risks at as low as possible. On the contrary, in shared economies, the community â€˜upper handâ€™ still is not enough to overwhelm pitfalls. In other words, star ratings/complaints would only work as long as you still could.

Airbnb has many a time exposed to hidden camera scandals, or Uber and Grab have all too often involved in robberies, fatal risks, and sexual abuse [7].

A report secondarily cited that the development of shared economies catalyzed a personnel â€˜flightâ€™ from traditional corporations - sooner or later, technology drivers would predominate, the quality would vitiate, the driver would earn less, and ultimately, the washed-out promotion fund would desperately soar service fees [8].

It is indeed what happening and the Vietnam market is reflecting this all too well. Technology corps have begun to cut driver rewards, raised service fees, and curbed promotions, paving the very way for the insurmountable complaints on drivers.

3. What we can, and can not change

On the whole, a shared economy has the two major advantages. First, from a consumer perspective, this innovative economic model is drastically leveraging service quality and costs. And two, from a macro-scale, it is indeed providing jobs for the idle/unemployed in society, serving as an inherent pressure that gets traditional corporations to change, proactively apply technology and become attentive to service quality to customers instead of purely internal processes.

Nonetheless, given the short-term benefits, the future of such a model still appears hazy. After all, anything does have 2 sides, and our taking it into careful consideration is neither to bring down nor do away with; it is rather to see if we can do anything to that future.

As mentioned at the beginning of the article and a recent post [9], the sharing economy is sooner or later catalyzing an inordinate number of precariats and gig workers.

Contrary to the idea of â€‹â€‹"sharing idle resources", the development of shared economy is essentially the use of new technologies and business types to create a competitive advantage in the labor market. Operating in a shared economy requires fewer licenses, regulations, and less processing time (which is indeed true for Uber and traditional taxi drivers, Airbnb hosts and hotel owners), having more customers and even offering higher incomes [10], thus, sucking in an enormous workforce.

By the book, those immersing in either Airbnb or Uber "should have" only participated for some times, to demonstrate, whilst having spare for-rent rooms, or part-timing as a hailing-app driver is to occupy idle hours and gain more income, many have been actually serious in taking Airbnb or Uber / Grab as their main jobs and feasting on that.

Which is no different from gambling their own future on the very platforms - formerly designed to protect full-time workers. For the most part, they have turned out, however, not paying insurance, having no sick leave, full-time "partnerâ€™s" servants and failing to meet other fundamental requirements in labor ownership. In addition, they are also receiving neither unemployment benefits nor other social benefits. They have been ousted from society, literally.

The "partners" pro tempore driven by money are hardly cognizant of their precarious future. Upon stormed by some accidents, sickness, or a ban o motorbikes, or a corrupt platform, they would bitterly realize they are hardly owning any competitiveness. After all, they would seem any less of a link for algorithmic monetization platforms. Engrossed in 12 hours on-the-go, how would they leveraged their driving skills after ten years?

According to statistics, nearly 50% of Uber drivers have college degrees, meaning that some people actually run Uber as a job to earn extra income, or many people have put their university degrees to be drivers, or both [11]. This is another feature of precariat / gig workers - people who have to do work below their level.

Another limitation, many view that sharing economy is very conducive to monopoly [12]. The advantage of technology startups in this area is the algorithms and money to launch promotions. When a successful company rises, it is very easy for it to quickly become a leader and create a big gap with competitors. Most of the economic sharing startups today are true to this view. And when monopolies occur, consumers' rights are no longer guaranteed. Bear in mind the story of Grab after beating Uber in the Vietnamese market.

Another thing, because it is the platform that connects peers, along with the deep intervention of algorithms, shared economic applications are subject to many allegations related to discrimination. According to many studies, blacks, Muslims and Asians in applications like Uber or Airbnb often have higher rejection rates than whites. [13]

The above limitations can be solved. Applications can change the algorithm so that it displays less of the information of service users to limit racial discrimination (and they did); policymakers can impose labor ownership regulations on these companies to protect workers (when the sharing economy is still as attractive as it is new).

Recently as it might seem, sharing economy, however, is exerting more profound impacts than that alone.

Airbnb is being called by a number of EU cities to boycott it, because it makes a profound change in the face of the urban community [14]. The appeal of Airbnb has caused long-term rental prices to rise, as many properties have been converted to serve short-term rentals. The land could not swell, especially in European cities, so more and more apartments joined Airbnb, and fewer and fewer apartments served local residents. In other words, fewer and fewer houses and inns are available.

One more thing, Airbnb's development is disrupting the community lifestyle. Tenants' short-lived and short-lived lifestyles, ranging from a few days to a few months, are making it harder for urban communities to stick around - and more complicated. This also makes management difficult, creating risks of population management. And quite oddly, research shows that Airbnb actually reduced the quality of local hotels [15].

A report of numerous studies [16] shows that the majority of those seeking economic services share an interest in economic factors (sellers find it easier to make money while buyers feel they can buy). services with lower levels), which has led to a gradual disregard for elements of communication and social interaction. That is, people are spending more money on solving their problems, and gradually taking human-person relationships with people like drivers or shipper (I think when you read this sentence, you also feel that get what I just mentioned).

Besides, contrary to the expectation that the interaction between strangers will increase social trust, the survey from the report also shows that many people feel insecure when having to receive and serve strangers. At the same time, things are even worse because the economic benefits of the sharing economy have undermined many social values, to demonstrate, many homeowners are bellyaching their frustration towards relatives visits for they are woefully affecting those very jobs.

In short, the most notable feature that makes the sharing economy so popular is that it addresses the economic needs of the majority of our population (both service providers and the clients). However, it seems that there are no insights that are unprejudiced and deep enough about their influence. All we do is the very profits in every single transaction.

The sharing economy is counted on as the very reformation of this society, which, however, still is appearing hazy. Something would be done away with, whilst others would emerge in replacement. After all, it still is unknown if it is indeed what we ultimately expect.

Which is not really new, for we have always been pushed under a "must step up" situation, given that hazy step might head us to nowhere?






